2014-02-27 00:07:50	-->	smrtz|nix (~smrtz@unaffiliated/smrtznix/x-9775867) has joined #zsh
2014-02-27 00:07:50	--	Topic for #zsh is "v5.0.5 | http://zsh.sf.net/ | http://zshwiki.org/ | http://zsh.sf.net/FAQ/ | http://zshwiki.org/home/docs/wikifaq | http://tinyurl.com/zsh-refcard-pdf | Just ask. | Nobody here or everybody clueless? try the zsh-users mailinglist: http://www.zsh.org/mla"
2014-02-27 00:07:50	--	Topic set by thrig (thrig@unaffilaited/thrig) on Thu, 16 Jan 2014 15:37:54
2014-02-27 00:07:50	--	Channel #zsh: 317 nicks (0 ops, 0 voices, 317 normals)
2014-02-27 00:07:50	--	PvNotice(ChanServ): Welcome to #zsh! Discussion of the Z Shell and sharing of configs highly encouraged. Enjoy your stay and come back soon!
2014-02-27 00:07:50	--	URL for #zsh: http://www.zsh.org/
2014-02-27 00:07:52	--	Mode #zsh [+cnt]
2014-02-27 00:07:52	--	Channel created on Tue, 02 Sep 2003 11:34:53
2014-02-27 00:08:16	smrtz|nix	Hey, everyone's telling me how zsh is better than bash, but no one will tell me why.  What improvments does it make?
2014-02-27 00:09:43	OODavo	http://zsh.sourceforge.net/FAQ/zshfaq03.html#31 is the initial biggest boon for scripting. Interactively, the extremely powerful completion system would be the first big selling point.
2014-02-27 00:10:21	smrtz|nix	Ahh, ok.  Thanks OODavo, I'll check the link.
2014-02-27 00:10:23	OODavo	Then there's things like the supercharged file globbing -- nearly everything you do with the 'find' command can be written using a zsh glob instead.
2014-02-27 00:11:03	smrtz|nix	why would you want that?  Wouldn't it make more since to use something more cross compatable?
2014-02-27 00:12:26	OODavo	Interactively, concision in expression wins over compatibility.
2014-02-27 00:13:03	OODavo	In scripts, it's a bit of a different story, but if you need POSIX-compliant scripts anyway you aren't going to get a scripting benefit from *any* shell besides /bin/sh.
2014-02-27 00:14:36	<--	druonysus (~drew@unaffiliated/druonysus) has quit (Remote host closed the connection)
2014-02-27 00:17:18	IAmTheClaw	smrtz|nix: you can complete paths like this in zsh: /u/l/e/ng/ng<tab> -> /usr/local/etc/nginx/nginx.conf
2014-02-27 00:17:28	IAmTheClaw	instead of doing each directory at a time
2014-02-27 00:17:43	OODavo	^
2014-02-27 00:18:18	OODavo	Also, completion possibilities appear in a menu you can cycle through, unlike bash's approach of just printing them all out.
2014-02-27 00:21:26	OODavo	And you can do this in your .zshrc: zstyle ':completion:*:default' list-colors ${(s.:.)LS_COLORS}
2014-02-27 00:21:44	OODavo	Which makes the completion menu colour directories/files/executables/etc. the same way ls --color=auto would.
2014-02-27 00:23:38	<--	DaveQB (~quassel@ppp255-134.static.internode.on.net) has quit (Ping timeout: 264 seconds)
2014-02-27 00:23:55	OODavo	It's a little thing but also a really, really useful one.
2014-02-27 00:25:28	-->	DaveQB (~quassel@ppp255-134.static.internode.on.net) has joined #zsh
2014-02-27 00:29:20	<--	gigetoo (~gigetoo@c83-250-61-4.bredband.comhem.se) has quit (Remote host closed the connection)
2014-02-27 00:30:18	-->	gigetoo (~gigetoo@c83-250-61-4.bredband.comhem.se) has joined #zsh
